 had previously been a life-altering journey undertaken slowly and incrementally over years, became a shorter, safer, trip characterized by round trip plane rides. In examining the transformation of the Nigerian Hajj, this book demonstrates how the Hajj became ever more intertwined with Nigerian politics and governance as the country moved from empire to independence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDecolonizationzNigeria. 0aMuslim pilgrims and pilgrimageszNigeriaxHistoryy19th century. 0aMuslim pilgrims and pilgrimageszNigeriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMuslim pilgrims and pilgrimageszSaudi ArabiazMeccaxHistoryy19th century. 0aMuslim pilgrims and pilgrimageszSaudi ArabiazMeccaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Africa / West.2bisacsh  aAhmadu Bello.  aHajj.  aMuhammadu Dikko.  aNigerian Pilgrimage Scheme.  aNorthern People's Congress.  acorruption.  adecolonisation.  aindirect rule.  apilgrimage.  atransnationalism.1 aMatthew M., Heaton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616261840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526162618423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526162618/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles